<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence from Headway Cambridgeshire (TIC 093)</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'HelveticaNeueLT Com 55 Roman'; font-size:14pt; text-decoration:underline">Written evidence from Headway Cambridgeshire (TIC 093)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:21.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'HelveticaNeueLT Com 55 Roman'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">About Headway Ca</span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:'HelveticaNeueLT Com 55 Roman'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">mbridgeshire, and Approach to this Response</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Headway Cambridgeshire provides specialist social rehabilitation services and support to people with a brain injury and other neurological conditions and their families, across the county and in Peterborough.  </span><span style="font-family:'HelveticaNeueLT Com 55 Roman'; font-size:11pt">We </span><span style="font-family:'HelveticaNeueLT Com 55 Roman'; font-size:11pt">work closely with health, social care, the independent sector and other agencies to ensure services are as seamless as possible.   We provide this help right through the support pathway:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'HelveticaNeueLT Com 55 Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#b2a1c7; font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">At the major trauma centre at </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Addenbrooke’s</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Hospital, Cambridge</span></li><li style="color:#b2a1c7; font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">At our hubs in Cambridge, Peterborough and Huntingdon</span></li><li style="color:#b2a1c7; font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Through our community services offering information, advice and guidance</span></li><li style="color:#b2a1c7; font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Through 1:1 support in people’s homes </span></li><li style="color:#b2a1c7; font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Through our vocational services helping clients get ‘work-ready’ if it is appropriate for them to do so.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 75pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Overall, we currently support 109 hub-based client placements each week and last year we had 1,500 contacts with our community clients.   Our turnover for 2013-14 is forecast as £617,000.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The population of Cambridgeshire and Peterborough combined is 831,000 (2011 census).  Cambridgeshire is a large county and extremely rural in parts (the Fens in particular), and there are many isolated communities.  It should be noted that because of their head injury and the consequent impairments, our clients are particularly vulnerable and lacking in confidence and sometimes the skills to engage with their local communities. This makes our client group particularly isolated, as well as the geographic areas in which they live.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We set up a number of client focus groups to discuss transport issues and what follows includes this feedback as well as the experience of the organisation. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.5</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The common themes from client discussion were:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#b2a1c7; font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Having to give notice prior to travelling on trains if you have a disability – not able to be spontaneous and decide on the day</span></li><li style="color:#b2a1c7; font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Many buses don’t lower /  have poor disabled access</span></li><li style="color:#b2a1c7; font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Lack of awareness / publicity about what is available including around disabled bus passes</span></li><li style="color:#b2a1c7; font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Although consultation around isolated communities there was an acknowledgement that community transport in urban areas (particularly Cambridge) was generally good with good access.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">SUMMARY</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:21.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We acknowledge some good public and community transport schemes in Cambridgeshire and Peterborough that works well for our disabled clients.  However we would like to see:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#b2a1c7; font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 66.76pt; padding-left:5.24pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">More consistency across the county, particularly when it comes to having disabled-friendly transport </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ie</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> enough space for wheelchairs and large walking frames.</span></li><li style="color:#b2a1c7; font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 66.76pt; padding-left:5.24pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Personal Independence Payment should take into account access to public or demand-responsive transport will vary significantly if you live in an isolated rural area compared to the centre of a large town.</span></li><li style="color:#b2a1c7; font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 66.76pt; padding-left:5.24pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Affordable and accessible public transport is key</span></li><li style="color:#b2a1c7; font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 66.76pt; padding-left:5.24pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Volunteer drivers are appreciated and considered “lovely” by clients</span></li><li style="color:#b2a1c7; font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 66.76pt; padding-left:5.24pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Client access to our rehabilitation services has been significantly affected because of costly transport.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">RESPONSE</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:21.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">How do Government and local authorities identify demand for passenger transport in isolated communities?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">3.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We welcome Cambridge County Council’s current consultation on their transport strategy and we will respond to that in due course.  What we would like to see, is more thought about how major transport infrastructure is implemented.  For instance the Cambridgeshire Guided </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Busway</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> introduced in 2011 and the longest guided bus route in the world, costing £181 million, has its problems for those physically less able.  One of our clients travels from Cambridge to his friend in St Ives.  He can get on the guided bus in Cambridge, but there is a big step down from the bus at the station in St Ives which is very difficult to manage.  Other clients found this disappointing and surprising considering how new the route is and how much it cost.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:21.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">To what extent are the needs of different groups of passengers taken into account in determining the provision of public transport to isolated communities?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">4.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In Cambridgeshire there are very isolated villages, and although </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Teversham</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is not far from Cambridge, one client who lives in the village said “Our village bus has stopped running.  If my husband didn’t have a car, I’d be house-bound and without the money for a taxi, I wouldn’t be able to access Headway rehabilitation services.  I can’t imagine my life without Headway.”</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">4.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Our clients are heavily reliant on public transport wherever they live.  One or two are able to  cycle and very few, because of the nature of their injury, are able to drive. However, if you are not able to work and live off a mixture of benefits, affordable public transport is a key issue.  If it is available, it has to be suitable, as one client said, “I can’t get on a bus if the two wheelchair allocated spaces are already taken.”</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:21.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">What are the main challenges associated with providing better and more consistent bus and rail services to isolated communities?  How can these challenges be overcome?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">5.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We think one of the main challenges is the lack of consistency in the provision of disabled access, for instance one client told us, “The bus arrived in Melbourne to take me to my hospital appointment at </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Addenbrooke’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> hospital.  It was a replacement bus, the usual one had a puncture, and didn’t have a wheelchair ramp.  I couldn’t get on the bus.  I missed my appointment.”</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">5.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Another said, “I choose to use trains and not buses because I am visually impaired and don’t know which bus is coming when it approaches.  If there were a system telling me at the bus stop the destination of the next bus, then I’d know to put out my hand.  Also, once on the bus, I don’t know where to get off.  Whereas on the train the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">next station is announced.  I am lucky to have a local train service.  Were I dependent on buses, I’d be stuck at home.”</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">5.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This was a common factor for all those visually impaired. Buses proved difficult to use; they may be able to see the bus coming, but they couldn’t see the destination on the front nor read a timetable.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">5.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There is good provision but it is patchy and if you live in villages there are often no buses, or very few each day.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">5.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Other feedback talked about the unreliability of public transport; it was expensive and there was no choice!  One of our clients even complained about the bad swearing by the bus drivers, in “many different languages”.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:21.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">How effectively do Community Transport services address the needs of passengers in isolated communities?  How could Community Transport be improved? </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">6.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Community transport is often heavily relied upon and volunteer drivers were praised, although one of our clients felt that the cost was still too expensive (the cost of petrol only).</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">6.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">However, our services heavily rely on volunteer drivers, co-ordinated by the County Council for the majority of our hub-based clients.  It could be improved if it was more ‘joined up’ in two very obvious ways: 1) by one car collecting clients from the same area in one trip rather than have two separate cars collecting two different clients and 2) if there was more sharing amongst non-urgent patient transport (NHS) and social care, or even other agencies who transport clients to and from their homes to support services.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:21.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">To what extent should passengers in isolated communities be expected to rely on taxis and other demand-responsive transport services?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">7.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">To some extent it is inevitable that if you are geographically isolated, you cannot expect the same level of transport service you would receive living in the centre of Cambridge where transport services are good.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">7.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">However, Personal Independence Payments (PIP) that includes daily living and mobility elements, do not reflect where you live so assuming you had the same impairment you would receive the same payment whether you lived in the centre of Cambridge or in the Fens.  So if you lived in Cambridge you could access a disabled-friendly bus for £3 a return journey if around the City, but in the Fens you would be lucky to access any bus and it would cost a lot more than £3 for a return journey to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Wisbech</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> for instance.  A client is expected to pay for taxis with their PIP but this is not realistic even assuming the taxi was disabled-friendly, because of the cost.  The current system is inequitable and Headway Cambridgeshire would like to see increased daily living and mobility payments for those living in isolated communities.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:21.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">What are the main challenges associated with funding transport services in isolated communities?  How can these services be made more affordable?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">8.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The biggest challenge has to be the pressure on the County Council’s budget.  We have seen a significant decline in referrals by the County Council for clients </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">accessing our services because of the cost of transport, which can cost more than the daily cost of access to our services.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">8.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In 2011 Cambridgeshire County Council (Adult Social Services) reduced our fees by 3% and they have not increased since. Open discussion with the commissioners has revealed that it is the cost of transport that is driving the cut in access to our services (a fall in income of  £45,000) since 2011. Their policy is that they will no longer support any transport costs to access our services. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">8.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As a response, we have introduced an additional service based in the client’s own home, and whilst the County will not be paying the transport costs directly, we have had to incorporate the cost of staff travel into the fee.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">8.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">However, one of the very important elements in our social rehabilitation model, is peer support and a reduction in social isolation.  We offer strategies to support clients improve their confidence and cognitive competence,  and ability to moderate sometimes challenging behaviour that can isolate them from their communities, so hub-based services for many clients (not all) is essential to ensure clients live well and get the most out of life.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">8.4 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We think existing transport services can be made more affordable by a more joined up approach and working with non urgent medical transport and other agencies transporting clients or patients around the county.  But this needs a shared will to do this and a preparedness to be more radical rather than ‘tinkering around the edges’ of a very fundamental problem in a very rural county.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>